  "prompt": "What should I do if my PayPal account is hacked?",
  "response": "If you suspect that your PayPal account has been hacked, follow these steps to secure your account and protect your financial information:\n\n1. **Change Your Password**: Immediately log into your PayPal account (if you can) and change your password. Use a strong, unique password that you haven't used before.\n\n2. **Enable Two-Factor Authentication**: If you haven't already done so, enable two-factor authentication (2FA) for added security. This adds an extra layer of protection by requiring a code sent to your phone or email in addition to your password.\n\n3. **Check Your Account Activity**: Review your account for any unauthorized transactions. If you find any, make a note of them.\n\n4. **Report Unauthorized Transactions**: If you see any suspicious activity or transactions that you did not authorize, report them to PayPal immediately. You can typically do this through the Resolution Center on their website.\n\n5. **Contact PayPal Support**: If you're unable to access your account or if you have any concerns, contact PayPal customer support for assistance. They can help you recover your account and investigate any unauthorized activity.\n\n6. **Review Linked Accounts**: Check any linked bank accounts or credit cards for unauthorized transactions and consider monitoring them closely or changing their passwords.\n\n7. **Scan for Malware**: Run a security scan on your devices to check for malware or viruses that may have compromised your security. Ensure you have up-to-date antivirus software installed.\n\n8. **Check for Phishing Attempts**: Be cautious of any emails or messages that ask for personal information or urge you to click on links. Ensure the communication is genuinely from PayPal before responding or clicking.\n\n9. **Monitor Your Financial Statements**: Keep a close eye on your bank and credit card statements for any unusual transactions in the weeks following the incident.\n\n10. **Consider Additional Measures**: Depending on the extent of the breach, you might want to consider monitoring your credit report or placing a fraud alert.\n\nFollowing these steps can help secure your PayPal account and mitigate any potential damage caused by the hack.",
